ip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Nully","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Eamonn.","Irish: shortened form of   McNulty  ."],"variants":[{"name":"McNulty","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Aidan, Brennan, Brigid, Dermot, Dympna, Kieran, Michael Patrick, Niall.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac an Ultaigh</b> ‘son of the Ulsterman’. This is the name of a Donegal family originally from County Down. It has sometimes been Anglicized as   North  ."]}]},{"name":"Elisabeth","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The spelling of   Elizabeth   used in the Authorized Version of the New Testament, and in most modern European languages. This was the name of the mother of John the Baptist (Luke 1:60). Etymologically, the name means ‘God is my oath’, and is therefore identical with <i>Elisheba</i>, the name of the wife of Aaron according to the genealogy at Exodus 6:23. The final element seems to have been altered by association with Hebrew <i>shabbāth</i> ‘Sabbath’."],"variants":[{"name":"Elizabeth","meanings":["The usual spelling of   Elisabeth   in English. It is recorded in the medieval period, but was made popular by being borne by  Queen Elizabeth I  of England (  1533–1603 ). In the 20th century it again became extremely fashionable, partly because it was the name of  Elizabeth Bowes-Lyon  (  1900–2002 ), who in  1936  became Queen Elizabeth as the wife of King George VI, and after his death in  1952  achieved great public affection as Queen Mother for nearly half a century. Even more influentially, it is the name of her daughter  Queen Elizabeth II  (  b. 1926 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Elisabeth de Nully was born about 1190, in Reulle-Vergy, Côte-d'Or, Burgundy, France. She had at least 1 daughter with Hugues de Vergy II."},"et":{"Abt 1190–":"umbes 1190–Surnud","1185–1240":"1185–1240","1213–Female":"1213–Surnud","1190–Female":"1190–Surnud","1190":"1190","1213":"1213","1240":"1240","1185":"1185","Abt 1213":"umbes 1213","Abt 1190":"umbes 1190","Reulle-Vergy, Côte-d'Or, Burgundy, France":"Reulle-Vergy, Côte-d'Or, Bourgogne, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"Abt 1190–":"noin 1190–Kuollut","1185–1240":"1185–1240","1213–Female":"1213–Kuollut","1190–Female":"1190–Kuollut","1190":"1190","1213":"1213","1240":"1240","1185":"1185","Abt 1213":"noin 1213","Abt 1190":"noin 1190","Reulle-Vergy, Côte-d'Or, Burgundy, France":"Reulle-Vergy, Côte-d'Or, Bourgogne, Ranska"},"fr":{"Abt 1190–":"environ 1190–Décédée","1185–1240":"1185–1240","1213–Female":"1213–Décédée","1190–Female":"1190–Décédée","1190":"1190","1213":"1213","1240":"1240","1185":"1185","Abt 1213":"environ 1213","Abt 1190":"environ 1190","Reulle-Vergy, Côte-d'Or, Burgundy, France":"Reulle-Vergy, Côte-d'Or, Bourgogne, France","lifeSummary":"Elisabeth de Nully est née environ 1190, à Reulle-Vergy, Côte-d'Or, Bourgogne, France. Elle a eu au moins 1 fille avec Hugues de Vergy II."},"de":{"Abt 1190–":"um 1190–Verstorben","1185–1240":"1185–1240","1213–Female":"1213–Verstorben","1190–Female":"1190–Verstorben","1190":"1190","1213":"1213","1240":"1240","1185":"1185","Abt 1213":"um 1213","Abt 1190":"um 1190","Reulle-Vergy, Côte-d'Or, Burgundy, France":"Reulle-Vergy, Côte-d'Or, Burgund, Frankreich","lifeSummary":"Elisabeth de Nully wurde um 1190 in Reulle-Vergy, Côte-d'Or, Burgund, Frankreich geb